Whilst incest is reprehensible for many reasons its odd that congenital malformities are the main fear. For reference, the "Semipalatinsk Nuclear Test Site" is close enough to effect the nearby eponymous city. In an official report published: 11 births per 1000 (global average is about 4:1000) had observable malformity (Vakulchuk et al, IRME, 2014). In modern Japan, presuming these siblings have not had incestuous ancestry in the last 150 years there would be no transgenerational epigenetic retention (3 generation seperation) and an inbreeding coefficient of 25%, the probability of an inherited disorders by the likes of uniparental disomy remains unchanged but homozygosity has a significant increase. Thankfully populations like the American Amish and much of the Levant and Middle East act as longitudinal studies in inbreeding and its effects, so lets take Lebanon's: 5.5 per 1000.
